              "title": "AWS Global Infrastructure",
              "order": 2,
              "content": "AWS operates the world's most extensive global cloud infrastructure. Understanding how AWS structures its physical and logical infrastructure is fundamental for the Cloud Practitioner exam.\n\n**Regions:**\nAn AWS Region is a physical location in the world where AWS has clusters of data centers. Each AWS Region consists of multiple, isolated, and physically separate Availability Zones. As of 2024, AWS has 33+ Regions globally.\n\nWhen choosing a Region, consider:\n- **Compliance:** Data residency and regulatory requirements (e.g., GDPR requires EU data to stay in EU)\n- **Latency:** Choose Regions closest to your users for best performance\n- **Service Availability:** Not all AWS services are in all Regions\n- **Pricing:** Costs vary by Region\n\n**Availability Zones (AZs):**\nEach Region has 2–6 Availability Zones. An AZ is one or more discrete data centers with redundant power, networking, and connectivity. AZs within a Region are:\n- Physically separated (miles apart) — protects against disasters\n- Connected with ultra-low-latency fiber links\n- Used to build highly available applications (deploy across 2+ AZs)\n\n**Edge Locations:**\nAWS has 400+ Edge Locations (also called Points of Presence) used by Amazon CloudFront (CDN) and other services to cache content closer to users. Edge Locations are NOT the same as Regions or AZs.\n\n**Analogy:** Think of AWS Regions as countries, AZs as cities within those countries, and Edge Locations as local post offices — smaller, more numerous, focused on delivery speed.",
