              "id": "les-clf-01-03",
              "title": "AWS Shared Responsibility Model",
              "order": 3,
              "content": "The AWS Shared Responsibility Model defines who is responsible for what in the cloud. This is one of the most tested topics on the Cloud Practitioner exam.\n\n**AWS is responsible for 'Security OF the Cloud':**\n- Physical security of data centers\n- Hardware and global infrastructure\n- Virtualization layer\n- Managed service software (e.g., RDS database engine patches)\n\n**Customer is responsible for 'Security IN the Cloud':**\n- Data encryption and management\n- Identity and Access Management (IAM) configuration\n- Network and firewall configuration\n- Operating system patches (for EC2)\n- Application-level security\n\n**Comparison Table:**\n| Responsibility | AWS | Customer |\n|---|---|---|\n| Physical data center security | ✓ | ✗ |\n| Hardware maintenance | ✓ | ✗ |\n| Hypervisor/virtualization | ✓ | ✗ |\n| Guest OS patching (EC2) | ✗ | ✓ |\n| IAM configuration | ✗ | ✓ |\n| Data encryption | Provides tools | Customer decides |\n| Network ACLs / Security Groups | Provides service | Customer configures |\n| RDS engine patches | ✓ | ✗ |\n\n**Key insight:** For managed services (RDS, Lambda, S3), AWS takes MORE responsibility. For unmanaged services (EC2), customers take MORE responsibility.",
