              "title": "AWS Pricing Fundamentals",
              "order": 4,
              "content": "AWS uses a pay-as-you-go pricing model with no upfront costs for most services. Understanding the pricing models is essential for the exam.\n\n**Three Core Pricing Principles:**\n1. **Pay for what you use** — no termination fees, no long-term contracts required\n2. **Pay less when you reserve** — Reserved Instances and Savings Plans offer up to 72% discount\n3. **Pay less as you use more** — volume discounts (e.g., S3 tiered pricing)\n\n**EC2 Pricing Models:**\n- **On-Demand:** Pay by the hour or second, no commitments. Best for unpredictable workloads.\n- **Reserved Instances (RI):** 1 or 3-year commitment, up to 72% savings. Best for steady-state workloads.\n- **Savings Plans:** Flexible pricing, commit to a usage amount ($/hr) for 1 or 3 years. More flexible than RIs.\n- **Spot Instances:** Bid for unused EC2 capacity, up to 90% savings. Can be interrupted. Best for fault-tolerant batch jobs.\n- **Dedicated Hosts:** Physical servers dedicated to you. Required for certain software licenses.\n\n**Free Tier:**\nAWS offers a Free Tier with three types:\n- **Always Free:** Services like AWS Lambda (1M free requests/month) and DynamoDB (25 GB storage) are always free within limits.\n- **12 Months Free:** Services like EC2 (750 hours t2.micro/month) and S3 (5 GB) free for 12 months after signup.\n- **Trials:** Short-term free trials for specific services.\n\n**AWS Cost Tools:**\n- **AWS Pricing Calculator:** Estimate costs before deploying\n- **AWS Cost Explorer:** Visualize and analyze actual costs\n- **AWS Budgets:** Set budget alerts\n- **AWS Trusted Advisor:** Cost optimization recommendations",
