              "id": "les-clf-02-01",
              "title": "Amazon EC2 — Elastic Compute Cloud",
              "order": 1,
              "content": "Amazon EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) provides scalable virtual machines in the cloud. It is the cornerstone of AWS compute services and the most commonly tested service on the Cloud Practitioner exam.\n\n**What EC2 gives you:**\n- Virtual servers (instances) running Linux, Windows, or macOS\n- Full control of the operating system\n- Ability to install any software\n- Pay only for time the instance is running\n\n**EC2 Instance Families:**\n| Family | Use Case | Examples |\n|---|---|---|\n| General Purpose | Balanced compute/memory/networking | t3, m6i |\n| Compute Optimized | CPU-intensive workloads | c6i, c7g |\n| Memory Optimized | Large in-memory databases | r6i, x2idn |\n| Storage Optimized | High I/O storage workloads | i4i, d3 |\n| Accelerated Computing | GPU/ML workloads | p4, g5, inf2 |\n\n**EC2 Key Concepts:**\n- **AMI (Amazon Machine Image):** Template for your instance (OS + pre-installed software)\n- **Instance Type:** Defines CPU, memory, storage, networking capacity\n- **Key Pair:** SSH key for secure access to Linux instances\n- **Security Group:** Virtual firewall controlling inbound/outbound traffic\n- **Elastic IP:** Static public IP address you can assign to an instance\n- **User Data:** Scripts that run when the instance launches (for bootstrapping)\n\n**Auto Scaling:** Automatically adds or removes EC2 instances based on demand, ensuring both availability and cost efficiency. Works with an Application Load Balancer (ALB) for traffic distribution.",
