              "title": "AWS Database Services Overview",
              "order": 3,
              "content": "AWS offers a wide portfolio of database services covering relational, NoSQL, caching, graph, ledger, and time-series databases. Understanding which service to use for which scenario is key for the exam.\n\n**Relational Databases (SQL):**\n- **Amazon RDS:** Managed relational database supporting MySQL, PostgreSQL, MariaDB, Oracle, SQL Server, and Amazon Aurora. AWS handles backups, patching, and Multi-AZ failover.\n- **Amazon Aurora:** AWS's own cloud-native relational database. MySQL and PostgreSQL compatible but 3x (MySQL) to 5x (PostgreSQL) faster. Automatically replicates across 3 AZs, 6 copies of data.\n\n**NoSQL Databases:**\n- **Amazon DynamoDB:** Fully managed, serverless NoSQL database. Key-value and document model. Single-digit millisecond performance at any scale. Auto-scales.\n- **Amazon ElastiCache:** In-memory caching using Redis or Memcached. Used to speed up read-heavy applications.\n\n**Purpose-Built Databases:**\n- **Amazon Redshift:** Data warehouse for analytics and BI. Query petabytes of structured data using SQL.\n- **Amazon DocumentDB:** MongoDB-compatible document database.\n- **Amazon Neptune:** Graph database for connected data (social networks, fraud detection).\n- **Amazon Timestream:** Time-series database for IoT data.\n- **Amazon QLDB:** Ledger database with immutable, cryptographically verifiable transaction log.\n\n**Comparison Table:**\n| Scenario | Best Service |\n|---|---|\n| Traditional app with SQL schema | RDS |\n| High-performance relational DB | Aurora |\n| Flexible NoSQL at scale | DynamoDB |\n| Reduce database load with cache | ElastiCache |\n| Business intelligence and reporting | Redshift |\n| Store product catalogs as documents | DocumentDB |",
