              "content": "AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) is the foundational security service that controls who can access what in your AWS account. It is one of the most heavily tested topics on the Cloud Practitioner exam.\n\n**IAM Core Components:**\n\n**Users:** Individual people or services that need AWS access. Each user has:\n- Credentials: Password (console) and/or Access Keys (CLI/API)\n- No permissions by default — must be explicitly granted\n\n**Groups:** Collections of users. Assign permissions to a group and all members inherit those permissions. Best practice: assign permissions to groups, not individual users.\n\n**Roles:** Identity that can be assumed by AWS services, applications, or users from other AWS accounts. Roles have temporary credentials and no passwords.\n- EC2 Role: Grants EC2 instances permission to call other AWS services\n- Cross-Account Role: Allows access from another AWS account\n- Service Role: Allows AWS services to act on your behalf (e.g., Lambda accessing S3)\n\n**Policies:** JSON documents that define permissions. Attached to users, groups, or roles.\n- **Allow:** Explicitly grants access\n- **Deny:** Explicitly blocks access (Deny ALWAYS overrides Allow)\n\n**IAM Best Practices:**\n1. Enable MFA (Multi-Factor Authentication) on the root account immediately\n2. Never use the root account for daily tasks — create admin IAM users\n3. Apply the Principle of Least Privilege (give only the minimum permissions needed)\n4. Use IAM Roles for EC2 instances, Lambda, and services (never embed access keys)\n5. Rotate access keys regularly\n6. Use IAM Access Analyzer to identify unintended access\n7. Enable CloudTrail to log all API calls\n\n**IAM is Global:** IAM users, groups, roles, and policies are global — not tied to a specific Region.",
              "key_points": [
                "IAM controls WHO can do WHAT in your AWS account",
                "Users = people, Groups = collections of users, Roles = assumed identities for services",
                "Policies = JSON permission documents; Deny always overrides Allow",
                "Best practice: MFA on root, least privilege, use roles for services"
              ],
