              "content": "Designing for high availability (HA) and disaster recovery (DR) is critical in cloud architecture. AWS provides multiple tools and patterns to achieve resilience.\n\n**Key Concepts:**\n- **High Availability (HA):** System remains operational despite component failures, typically within the same Region.\n- **Fault Tolerance:** System continues working even when components fail — requires redundancy at every layer.\n- **Disaster Recovery (DR):** Ability to recover from catastrophic events affecting an entire Region.\n\n**HA Design Patterns:**\n1. Deploy across multiple AZs (protects against single data center failure)\n2. Use Auto Scaling to replace failed instances automatically\n3. Use managed services (RDS Multi-AZ, Aurora) that handle HA automatically\n4. Front-end with an Elastic Load Balancer to distribute traffic\n\n**DR Strategies (cheapest to most resilient):**\n| Strategy | RTO | RPO | Cost | Description |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Backup & Restore | Hours | Hours | $ | Periodic backups to S3, restore when needed |\n| Pilot Light | ~10 min | Minutes | $$ | Core services always running, scale up on disaster |\n| Warm Standby | Minutes | Seconds | $$$ | Scaled-down production copy always running |\n| Multi-Site Active-Active | Near zero | Near zero | $$$$ | Full production running in two Regions |\n\n**Key Metrics:**\n- **RTO (Recovery Time Objective):** Maximum time to restore operations after a disaster\n- **RPO (Recovery Point Objective):** Maximum acceptable data loss measured in time",
