              "content": "The AWS Cloud Adoption Framework (CAF) provides guidance for organizations planning cloud migrations. Understanding it is useful for the Cloud Practitioner exam.\n\n**AWS Cloud Adoption Framework (CAF) — 6 Perspectives:**\n1. **Business:** Align IT with business objectives. Stakeholders: CFO, CEO, CTO.\n2. **People:** Change management, training, culture. Stakeholders: HR, Staffing.\n3. **Governance:** Portfolio management, risk, audit. Stakeholders: CIO, Enterprise Architects.\n4. **Platform:** Architecture, technology decisions. Stakeholders: CTOs, Architects.\n5. **Security:** IAM, compliance, infrastructure protection. Stakeholders: CISOs.\n6. **Operations:** Monitoring, incident management. Stakeholders: IT Operations managers.\n\n**The 7 Rs of Migration (Cloud Migration Strategies):**\n| Strategy | Description | Example |\n|---|---|---|\n| Retire | Decommission unneeded apps | Shut down unused systems |\n| Retain | Keep on-premises for now | Legacy mainframe systems |\n| Rehost (Lift & Shift) | Move as-is to cloud | Move VMs to EC2 |\n| Relocate | Move entire platform as-is | VMware Cloud on AWS |\n| Repurchase | Switch to SaaS | Move CRM to Salesforce |\n| Replatform | Minor cloud optimizations | Move DB to RDS |\n| Refactor/Re-architect | Redesign for cloud-native | Microservices on Lambda/EKS |\n\n**AWS Migration Services:**\n- **AWS Migration Hub:** Track migrations across multiple tools\n- **AWS Database Migration Service (DMS):** Migrate databases with minimal downtime\n- **AWS Server Migration Service (SMS):** Migrate on-premises virtual machines\n- **AWS Snowball:** Transfer large datasets physically when internet is too slow",
